<TEXT>
financial shortfalls may force 
argentina latin americas leading user of nuclear power to halt 
construction on a third nuclear reactor and a heavywater plant its 
top nuclear official says 
plans are being made to stop work on the nuclear reactor atucha 
ii which is 60 percent completed and arroyito 90 percent 
finished unless financing is obtained or the government agrees to a 
800 million budget request said emma perez ferreira president of 
the national atomic energy commission 
well have to stop work on the big ones first if we dont get 
enough money or obtain financing for the projects ms perez 
ferreira argentinas topranking female government official said 
in a recent interview 
a shutdown could hurt argentinas nuclear industry which is the 
most advanced in the western hemisphere outside the united states 
and canada and cut into its future sales of surplus heavy water 
argentina has a contract to build a 100million 10megawatt 
nuclear reactor outside lima peru it also has contracts to build a 
nuclear reactor in algeria and to provide enriched uranium for a 
small experimental nuclear reactor at irans tehran university ms 
perez ferreira said 
argentinas nuclear technicians have mastered the entire fuel 
cycle which gives them the ability to make nuclear weapons but 
officials from president raul alfonsin on down deny this is in their 
plans 
at one time the nuclear program was closely tied to the armed 
forces in particular the navy an admiral headed the atomic energy 
commission until the early 1980s and some reports at the time said 
the military favored building an atomic bomb 
argentina mines its own uranium ore in the andes it prepares its 
own fuel and is capable of enriching the fuel making fuel 
elements running nuclear reactors and reprocessing the fuel 
enriching and reprocessing fuel are the keys to making nuclear 
weapons 
argentina the worlds eighthlargest country geographically has 
two existing nuclear power plants until its economic crisis 
worsened last year it had dreams of building four power plants by 
the end of the century 
theres no sense in talking now even about a fourth nuclear 
plant ms perez ferreira said argentina also has an 
uraniumenrichment plant six research reactors and two reprocessing 
plants 
the nuclear program is important to argentina providing up to 20 
percent of its electrical power and is a source of pride to a 
country whose standard of living has declined steadily since the 
1950s 
but now argentina is the developing worlds thirdlargest debtor 
behind brazil and mexico owing 55 billion it also has a 247 
percent inflation rate in addition to other severe economic 
problems including a loss of real wages for workers 
indeed 22 percent of atomic energy commissions 6500member 
work force have left their jobs since 1983 many for similar posts 
offering double their pay in switzerland brazil and the united 
states ms perez ferreira said 
neighboring brazil has a nuclearpower program but its sole plant 
near rio de janeiro has had constant troubles plans to build two 
other nuclear plants have been set aside for the time being 
ms perez ferreira a 52yearold nuclear physicist took over 
the commission last year when her predecessor quit over budgetary 
disputes with the government as head of commission she reports 
directly to president alfonsin 
although officials deny any plans for nuclear weapons argentina 
has yet to sign the international nuclear nonproliferation treaty 
it opposes the treaty on grounds that it interferes with national 
sovereignty the other nonsignatory nations with nuclear technology 
are south africa israel india pakistan and brazil 
accidents at argentine nuclear facilities have left three 
technicians dead since 1982 but experts say argentina is not 
considered unsafe a radioactive water spill and a burst pipe also 
briefly shut down atucha i and the embalse plant last year and in 
may 
national reliance on nucleargenerated power became apparent in 
april when power shortages caused in part by temporary shutdowns of 
atucha i and embalse forced emergency power cutoffs in buenos aires 
mar del plata and other major cities 
argentinas nuclear interest stems from 1950 during the first 
presidency of juan d peron its first power plant was atucha i a 
335megawatt facility built with west german technology in 1974 
the second embalse outside cordoba in northcentral argentina 
was finished in 1983 built with canadian technology it has 600 
megawatts of power equal to the connecticut yankee plant in the 
united states 
atucha ii if it is completed will have 745 megawatts 
</TEXT>
