<TEXT>
this years drought in the west is grim news 
for north american ducks battered throughout the 1980s by bad 
weather in breeding areas warns the fish and wildlife service 
drought is hurting prime duck breeding areas in the dakotas 
alaska montana and the canadian provinces of alberta manitoba 
saskatchewan and british columbia not only by drying up marshy 
areas where ducks breed but by enticing cattle to graze in areas 
they normally wouldnt reach and by leading farms to put such areas 
under the plow 
the situation looks grim said frank dunkle director of the 
service 
if preliminary results of the annual survey of nesting areas 
done in cooperation with canadian authorities are borne out later 
this summer the service will have to take a hard look at 
hunting regulations for the fall he said 
the survey of duck broods in july forms the basis for each years 
hunting regulations in 1985 the survey cut seasons and bag limits 
sharply 
duck populations in the survey areas used to range well above 40 
million but they fell in the 1980s to an alltime low of 30 million 
in 1985 before rebounding slightly to 34 million to 35 million 
bob blohm assistant chief of the survey branch said in a 
telephone interview from the servicess patuxent md research 
station that results were still coming in from this years survey 
particularly from northerly areas he said he could not predict what 
the final count will be but the prospect for a large number of 
offspring this year is dim 
many ducks returning from the south this spring discovering 
their normal breeding areas drier than normal may have found 
nesting areas farther north there is a question though of how 
productive they are when they do that blohm said 
many areas experienced a mild dry fall and winter followed by 
low precipitation and strong winds this spring according to a 
statement by the service in southern canada poor conditions 
began as early as last summer when less than onethird of the 
prairie region received normal precipitation it is believed 
rainfall this late in the spring probably will not help much because 
the ground is so dry it will just soak up the water 
one study in a fivesquaremile area around woodworth nd 
indicated that only 38 percent of the basins had water and those 
levels were low the service said old wives lake in southcentral 
saskatchewan is dry for the first time since 1937 whitewater 
lake in southwest manitoba traditionally an important areas for 
ducks is only a quarter full 
the service said biologists were reporting congregations of 
ducks crowding into what water remains often with little nesting 
cover 
