<TEXT>
the first visit to moscow by a us president in 14 
years was overshadowed in the staterun media by a spirited 
discussion of domestic politics a debate that brought unprecedented 
developments and raised issues not heard since the 1920s 
the argument is over a nationwide communist party conference 
starting june 28 that is shaping up as a battleground for supporters 
of mikhail s gorbachevs reforms and the midlevel managers who 
oppose them 
entrenched bureaucrats fear the soviet leaders campaign to end 
party oversight of the daytoday details of governing and economic 
planning and give the people a greater role sociologist tatyana 
zaslavskaya said in an interview printed saturday by the newspaper 
izvestia 
a senior western diplomat said they have not debated issues as 
basic as this since the 1920s when the tyranny of josef stalin 
began 
last week gorbachevs policy of glasnost or greater 
openness was giving both the soviet people and the west an 
unprecedented look at the internal soviet debate 
in a week of firsts 
on saturday may 28 soviet television carried what is believed 
to be the first live broadcast of the presidium of the supreme 
soviet the nations parliament formally ratifying the treaty to 
scrap intermediaterange nuclear missiles which had been signed at 
the december summit 
president reagan arrived the next day becoming the first us 
president since gerald ford to visit the soviet union 
ousted politburo member boris n yeltsin in unprecedented 
interviews last monday with us and british broadcasters attacked 
politburo member yegor k ligachev as the main person 
responsible for slowing down the reforms 
that was only the beginning 
the moscow news reported that same day that vandals had smashed a 
jewish cemetery west of the capital and jewish residents said they 
feared rising antisemitism an unwelcome byproduct of greater 
openness 
