<TEXT>
a set of figures compiled by the central 
intelligence agency illustrates how brilliantly the economy of japan 
has performed in the 1980s compared with those of the united states 
and western europe 
in dealing with unemployment inflation production and foreign 
trade japan outshines the others even successful west germany the 
yens value has zoomed up at the same time that japanese interest 
rates have floated gently down 
the cia makes no comment on its information its directorate of 
intelligence issues a thin pamphlet every two weeks called 
economics and energy indicators it contains only blandlooking 
tables of figures and no analysis but the latest issue summarizes 
figures in the 1980s 
japanese success goes back to the end of world war ii and its 
due to a combination of things commented jeffrey j schott of the 
private institute for international economics 
theres readiness to adjust to changing circumstances theyre 
shifting now from exports to production for home use theres 
cooperative labor and management practices and theres just hard 
work theyre all interrelated 
japanese unemployment was a little above 2 percent at the start 
of the decade it has crept up a bit but never reached 3 percent 
in this country unemployment was 96 percent in 1982 three times 
japans it was even higher for a while during that years 
recession but has fallen since then 
still the us rate as given by the cia 56 percent in 
february is still more than twice as high as japans 27 percent 
unemployment in the four biggest countries of western europe 
varied widely from west germanys 77 percent in 1982 to italys 
124 percent last year 
cia figures do not always agree with those issued by other us 
government agencies and cia officials say they come from several 
sources the labor department reported that us consumer prices 
rose 44 percent in 1987 the cia put the number at 37 percent 
there are often many ways to calculate such statistics 
on inflation the cia showed consumer prices in the united states 
rising by 62 percent in 1982 although the increase was only 37 
percent last year it is climbing again according to the agency 
western europes record is similar on average although it 
differs widely from country to country earlier in the decade these 
rates averaged somewhat higher in europe than in the united states 
by 1987 the average was nearly the same 
but in japan the inflation rate never reached 3 percent last 
year japanese consumers paid an average of only onetenth of 1 
percent over the level of 1986 in 1988 prices are falling fairly 
sharply with the drop in february at an annual rate of 24 percent 
in 1982 the united states bought foreign goods worth 32 billion 
more than what it could sell abroad though for a while that year 
its trade was almost in balance imports rose so fast in the rest of 
the 1980s that in 1987 the us international trade deficit amounted 
to a record 153 billion 
japan started with a trade surplus of 19 billion in 1982 and 
rocketed to a record of 96 billion in 1987 the level drooped a 
little early last year but rose again through february 
the japanese performance wouldnt look so brilliant if our own 
had not been so unbrilliant said robert solomon of the brookings 
institution a major washington research group 
