<TEXT>
the supreme court expanding its study of drug 
testing in the workplace today agreed to decide whether the 
nations railroads may require all employees involved in serious 
accidents to take such tests 
the court will review a ruling that struck down as an 
unconstitutional invasion of privacy federal regulations requiring 
such drug tests for railroad employees 
the justices last february said they would decide whether the 
us customs service may conduct drug tests for those seeking 
drugenforcement jobs a federal appeals court upheld such testing 
today the justices said they will study the customs service and 
railroad employees cases together a decision is expected sometime 
in 1989 
the railroad drugtesting case stems from regulations issued by 
the federal railroad administration in 1985 to alleviate a 
significant safety problem caused by alcohol and drug use by rail 
employees 
the regulations generally require railroads to conduct blood and 
urine tests on employees directly involved in serious train 
accidents 
the regulations also authorize but do not require railroads to 
administer breath and urine tests after certain accidents incidents 
or rule violations 
the san franciscobased 9th us circuit court of appeals ruled 
last feb 11 that such tests conducted by private employers acting 
for the government are unreasonable searches banned by the 
constitutions fourth amendment 
the appeals court noted that the regulations require the testing 
of all members of a trains crew following certain accidents even 
in the absence of any particularized suspicion of drug or 
alcohol use 
accidents incidents or rule violations by themselves do not 
create reasonable grounds for suspecting that tests will demonstrate 
alcohol or drug impairment in any one railroad employee much less 
an entire train crew the appeals court said 
in the appeal acted on today reagan administration lawyers 
argued that the 9th circuit court was overstating the nature of 
employee privacy interests and understating the competing safety 
interests at stake 
in urging the justices to reinstate the federal drugtesting 
regulations the government lawyers said railroad accidents linked 
to drug or alcohol use killed 42 people injured 61 and caused 
property damages estimated at 19 million from 1972 through 1983 
the governments appeal said the railroad case raised issues that 
should be studied together with those presented in the customs 
service case 
the case is burnley vs railway labor executives association 
871555 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

