the supreme court today killed a bid by sen 
john melcher dmont to give the senate a bigger hand in naming 
members to a key federal committee that helps set monetary policy 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that dismissed a 
challenge to the way some members are appointed to the federal open 
market committee 
the committee part of the federal reserve system directs the 
buying and selling of government securities in the open market by 
federal reserve banks 
the committees 12 members consist of the seven governors of the 
federal reserve board and five representatives of federal reserve 
banks 
the federal reserve board governors are appointed by the 
president with senate approval the five others are selected 
annually by the boards of directors of the reserve banks from among 
the banks presidents and first vice presidents 
melcher filed a lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of how 
the the five bank executives are named to the committee he said 
they also should be subject to senate confirmation 
the us court of appeals threw out the suit last december the 
court said ruling on the merits of melchers claim would represent 
undue judicial interference with the legislative process 
any change in the appointment of committee members must be left 
to congress the appeals court said adding that similar challenges 
by other other senators met with a similar fate 
melcher said the changing national and world economy has given 
the issue a greater urgency than ever as the federal reserve 
grows in importance so does the injury to this plaintiff in the 
deprivation of his rightful constitutional role in the selection of 
the officers who control it he said 
the case is melcher vs federal open market committee 871546 
