<TEXT>
the supreme court refused 63 today to order 
states to give refunds to businesses when a state tax is invalidated 
as a violation of interstate commerce 
the justices turned down an appeal asking them to apply 
retroactively a 1987 ruling in which the high court struck down a 
washington state manufacturing tax that favored some instate 
businesses 
justices byron r white john paul stevens and antonin scalia 
voted to hear arguments in the case but four votes are needed for 
review 
the court ruled last year that the washington tax discriminated 
unlawfully against interstate commerce because the levy in effect 
was assessed only on products manufactured in washington and sold to 
outofstate customers 
two dissenting justices said then that the decision could 
revolutionize the law of state taxation by drastically limiting 
the states discretion to structure their tax systems 
the court sent the case back to the washington supreme court to 
determine whether the ruling should be applied retroactively 
thereby forcing the state to refund taxes to businesses that paid 
the revenue 
the state court ruled last january that the businesses are not 
entitled to refunds 
state officials estimated that refunds from 1980 through 1984 
could exceed 423 million if the state were forced to pay them 
the tax challenged by 70 businesses was imposed on gross 
receipts of all manufacturing within the state 
manufacturers selling their products outside the state were 
required to pay the tax but those selling products only within 
washingtons borders were exempt if they paid another gross receipts 
tax on wholesale or retail sales 
by paying either the wholesaling or retailing tax a wholly 
instate business thus gained an exemption from the state 
manufacturing tax at the same time companies doing interstate 
business received no such exemption when paying business taxes in 
other states 
companies that challenged the tax said that not forcing states to 
repay unlawful taxes would neutralize the effect of last years 
ruling and discourage businesses from challenging other unfair taxes 
the council of state chambers of commerce in support of the 
companies appeal said that in recent years state after state 
has been taking a back door prospectiveonly approach to adverse 
largedollar state tax test cases 
even if businesses win in court they end up losing because they 
do not receive any refunds the organization said 
the cases are national can corp vs washington 871629 and 
tyler pipe industries vs washington 871767 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

