<DOCNO> AP880606-0086 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today gave a boost to groups 
seeking to place referenda before state voters 
the justices ruled unanimously that states permitting such 
socalled initiatives may not prohibit groups from paying those who 
gather petition signatures necessary to get an issue on the ballot 
justice john paul stevens writing for the court said a colorado 
law that makes it a felony to pay those who circulate petitions is 
unconstitutional 
colorados prohibition of paid petition circulators restricts 
access to the most effective fundamental and perhaps economical 
avenue of political discourse he said 
many states permit citizens to place propositions on the ballot 
through the initiative process it has been particularly popular in 
the west as a means of encouraging direct democracy 
stevens said the colorado ban violates free speech rights of 
referenda supporters because it limits the number of voices who 
will convey the supporters message and the hours they can speak 
and therefore limits the size of the audience they can reach 
also stevens said requiring those who solicit signatures to be 
volunteers improperly reduces the chances the initiative will be 
placed before the voters limiting the groups ability to make 
the matter the focus of statewide discussion 
the court upheld an appeals court decision which struck down the 
colorado law 
the ban was challenged by coloradans for free enterprise a group 
seeking to deregulate the trucking industry the group said 
regulation of the industry by the state public utility commission 
had created an unfair monopoly that excluded competition 
the group sought in 1984 to place the deregulation initiative on 
the state ballot by accumulating 46737 signatures of registered 
voters on petitions or 5 percent of the states qualified voters 
the effort fell short as the state enforced its ban on paying 
people to round up the required signatures 
the ban was upheld by a federal judge but overturned by the 10th 
us circuit court of appeals 
state officials said paying signature solicitors violates 
grassroots petition drives by encouraging big spending and 
highpressure tactics by special interest groups 
they also said that paying people to gather signatures encourages 
fraud 
stevens said today there is no evidence to support the officials 
claims and added that there are adequate safeguards to prevent fraud 
the case is meyer vs grant 87920 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

