<TEXT>
the supreme court today expanded safeguards for 
workers who claim they were mistreated by employers 
the court ruled unanimously in a case from illinois that states 
may give protection to workers beyond that provided by federal labor 
law so long as it doesnt force courts to interpret collective 
bargaining agreements 
justice john paul stevens in his opinion for the court said 
federal law does not preclude such state lawsuits as long as the 
statelaw claim can be resolved without interpreting the collective 
bargaining agreement itself 
the court reinstated a suit by jonna lingle who was fired from 
her herrin ill job for filing what her employer said was a false 
claim for disability compensation 
ms lingle informed the norge division of magic chef in late 1984 
that she had sustained an injury while working at its plant she 
asked that norge pay her medical bills as provided for under the 
states workers compensation law 
norge fired her a week later asserting that she had filed a 
false claim 
ms lingle was represented by a union whose contract with norge 
protected workers against firings without just cause 
the day she was fired ms lingles union filed a grievance 
against norge an arbitrator ruled that her firing had been contrary 
to the contracts just cause provision and ms lingle was 
reinstated as a norge employee 
ms lingle also had sued norge pending the outcome of the 
grievance claim she said her firing violated illinois law 
the relief available to her under that state law is greater than 
the remedy she received in arbitration 
for example ms lingle could be awarded punitive damages against 
norge and could be compensated for lost overtime payments under the 
state law 
such awards were not available in the arbitration proeedings 
also ms lingle said she is entitled to additional relief under 
the state law because the job to which she was reinstated was not as 
desirable as the one she held before she was fired 
a federal trial judge threw out ms lingles lawsuit on grounds 
the state law is preempted by the federal labor management 
relations act of 1947 the 7th us circuit court of appeals upheld 
the judges ruling 
but stevens said today that a judge could decide under illinois 
law that ms lingle was fired illegally in retaliation for filing 
the workers compensation claim without deciding whether norge had 
violated the union contract 
the case is lingle vs norge 87259 
</TEXT>
