<DOCNO> AP880606-0093 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court set aside the death sentence 
of a convicted maryland murderer by a 54 vote today saying it 
could not be sure he received a fair sentence 
in a separate decision the court ruled unanimously that a 
convicted oklahoma killer was wrongly sentenced to death for having 
committed an especially heinous atrocious or cruel crime 
both ralph mills in maryland and william thomas cartwright in 
oklahoma are entitled to new sentencing trials the court said 
mills was in the second year of a 30year prison sentence for 
murder when he used a makeshift knife to kill paul robin brown in 
the cell they shared at a state prison in hagerstown md 
prison authorities said that prior to the aug 6 1984 murder 
mills had threatened to kill a previous cellmate if mills 
complaints about visiting rights and other matters were not resolved 
mills was convicted and sentenced to death for browns murder 
in challenging the sentence mills lawyers argued that jurors 
who sentenced him did not understand the judges instructions about 
determining whether any mitigating circumstances existed 
such mitigating factors indicate that life in prison rather than 
death is the appropriate punishment 
mills lawyers contended that the jurors thought they had to be 
unanimous in finding any mitigating circumstance and as a result 
found none 
mills appeal argued that if 11 jurors agreed that there were six 
mitigating circumstances but one juror found none the jury would 
have to report that no mitigating circumstance existed 
the result the appeal said could be that the death penalty was 
imposed even though 11 jurors might think it was wholly 
inappropriate 
the maryland court of appeals the states highest court ruled 
that the judges instructions to jurors could be read in a way that 
preserved mills death sentence 
but writing for the high court today justice harry a blackmun 
said there is a substantial probability that reasonable jurors 
in attempting to complete the verdict form as instructed may 
well have thought they were precluded from considering any 
mitigating evidence unless all 12 jurors agreed on the existence of 
a particular such circumstance 
if that were the case blackmun said it would violate past 
supreme court rulings that the sentencer must be permitted to 
consider all mitigating evidence 
the possibility that a single juror could block such 
consideration and consequently require the jury to impose the death 
penalty is one we dare not risk blackmun said 
joining him were justices william j brennan byron r white 
thurgood marshall and john paul stevens 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices sandra day 
oconnor antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy voted to uphold 
mills sentence 
the instructions on the sentencing form and the charges given 
to the jury in this case are unexceptionable and mills sentence 
should be upheld rehnquist said 
in the case from oklahoma cartwright was convicted of killing 
hugh riddle his former boss at riddles muskogee county home in 
1982 
the 10th us circuit court of appeals upheld cartwrights murder 
conviction but threw out his death sentence last year 
the appeals court ruled that oklahoma courts had interpreted part 
of the states death penalty law in an impermissibly overbroad way 
a view with which the supreme court unanimously agreed today 
oklahoma juries considering whether to impose death or life in 
prison for convicted murderers are told to weigh all aggravating 
circumstances against all mitigating circumstances 
one of eight aggravating circumstances specified under oklahoma 
law is whether the murder was especially heinous atrocious or 
cruel 
the supreme court ruled in 1980 that a similarly worded 
aggravating circumstance in georgia law could be applied only to 
cases in which the victim suffered serious physical abuse before 
death 
after cartwrights sentencing oklahoma courts have restricted 
the heinous atrocious or cruel language to those murders in 
which torture or serious physical abuse occurred 
justice byron r white writing for the court today said 
cartwrights sentence was based on an unconstitutionally vague 
aggravating circumstance 
the cases are mills vs maryland 875367 and maynard vs 
cartwright 87519 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
