an assistance program designed to bring 
telephone service to poor americans signed up nearly 14000 new 
subscribers in four target areas in the first six months of the 
program though a government report shows phone subscribership in 
three of those areas declined overall 
the program called link up america is a combined initiative 
of state and federal regulators consumer groups and telephone 
companies to bring phone service to the 5 million americans who 
dont have it 
since it was started last october 30 states and the district of 
columbia have developed programs certified by the federal 
communications commission residents of those states become eligible 
for benefits that include payment of up to half of their phone 
installation and connection charges up to 30 
the district of columbia and three states arkansas texas and 
west virginia were selected as target states to be monitored 
closely for six months so the fcc could assess the effectiveness of 
various marketing strategies that could be used in other areas 
link up america officials say the program signed up 5358 new 
subscribers in arkansas 455 in the district of columbia 5153 in 
texas and 3029 in west virginia 
a census bureau survey for the fcc shows that subscribership 
declined from march 1987 to march 1988 in arkansas from 87 percent 
to 836 percent of the population in texas from 904 percent to 
878 percent and in west virginia from 887 percent to 879 
percent in washington dc subscribership rose from 912 percent 
to 933 percent 
