the boeing 737 landed successfully without power may 24 without 
injuries to the 41 people aboard 
mondays takeoff was normal in all respects said warren v 
wandel a safety inspector for the national transportation safety 
board 
actually the fast steep ascent would have been a bit 
uncomfortable for passengers had there been any aboard 
the two boeing test pilots who flew the plane from its emergency 
landing strip to new orleans international airport practically stood 
the plane on its tail made a 15degree turn to the right and 
climbed quickly into low clouds lingering from two days of rain 
the plane landed safely at new orleans international about 15 
minutes later 
the narrow world war ii airstrip is now used as a road from a 
fuel tank assembly plant to a harbor on the intracoastal waterway a 
straightline shortcut from the gulf of mexico to the port at new 
orleans 
the may 24 emergency landing was made on a grassy strip parallel 
to the road 
the plane had lost power in both engines and the right one 
which showed some damage from overheating was replaced for takeoff 
wandel said the left engine would be removed at new orleans 
international and both engines would be taken apart next week and 
inspected 
of all the possible causes of the loss of power only fuel 
contamination has been ruled out wandel said it will be several 
months before the ntsb announces its findings he said 
getting approval to remove the plane from the insurers and all 
the federal state and local agencies involved was cumbersome there 
were discussions of taking the plane apart and trucking the pieces 
away as well as putting it aboard a barge and floating it to an 
airport 
