<TEXT>
in another sign of improving economic 
conditions the number of americans late on their mortgage payments 
fell to the second lowest level of this decade during the first 
three months of the year a trade group of lenders reported monday 
the mortgage bankers association said the number of mortgage 
payments late by 30 days or more dropped to 478 percent of total 
mortgages in the first quarter down from 495 percent in the last 
three months of 1987 
this was the second lowest latepayment level since 1979 
bettered only by a 471 percent deliquency rate in the third quarter 
of 1987 
the rate of foreclosures remained unchanged in the first quarter 
at 027 percent of all mortgages up slightly from the rate a year 
ago 
warren lasko executive vice president of the association said 
foreclosures remain a problem especially in economically 
depressed regions of the country but he said the steady drop in 
late payments should translate into lower foreclosures in quarters 
ahead 
all four regions of the country experienced lower latepayment 
levels in the first quarter when compared with the same period a 
year ago when the overall latepayment rate was 517 percent 
the largest decline was in the northeast where late payments 
fell from 444 percent a year ago to 381 percent in the 
januarymarch quarter the lowest level of any region 
the south which has been hard hit by troubles in energy 
producing states saw the level of late payments fall from 572 
percent down to 527 percent in the januarymarch quarter 
the midwest had a drop from 522 percent to 485 percent while 
the level of late payments in the west fell from 451 percent down 
to 417 percent in the first quarter 
