<TEXT>
gaps in insurance coverage a dearth of 
longterm care and lack of services for the poor are among the most 
pressing problems facing aids patients health professionals said 
monday 
our biggest problems are acute care for indigent aids patients 
and longterm custodial care katherine wright a care coordinator 
at the aids arms network in dallas told a senate committee 
wright said many aids patients die in the hospital because their 
insurance does not cover home care hospices are unavailable or 
nursing homes will not accept them 
she also cited gaps in the private and government insurance 
systems and said more than half the clients her organization sees 
spend themselves down to the poverty level to qualify for help from 
the statefederal medicaid program 
sen john glenn dohio chairman of the government affairs 
committee said the number of fullblown aids cases in the united 
states is expected to reach 450000 by 1993 
we must take steps now to meet the challenges presented by the 
tremendous increase in aids cases that is upon us he said 
glenn cited two recent reports recommending increased federal 
funding and involvement in the aids crisis one from the institute 
of medicine and the other from the chairman of the presidential 
commission on aids 
dr david sundwall adminstrator of the federal health resources 
and services administration said his agency is spending nearly 37 
million on aids grant programs this year and is requesting 40 
million for fiscal 1989 
he declined to say more money is needed but acknowledged that his 
agency receives about twice as many grant proposals as it can fund 
he also said some services fall short 
in order to to cope with the inevitable increasing burden 
were going to have to have better longterm care sundwall said 
sundwall said people are backed up in hospital beds in many 
regions because they dont have anywhere else to go he said the 
crunch is regional and his agency is considering numerous 
strategies among them block grants to states based on their number 
of aids cases 
ideally a comprehensive aids service delivery network would 
include hospital services outpatient physician or clinic services 
home health care subacute skilled nursing inhome support 
services mental health services and counseling housing 
employment legal and financial services sundwall said 
dr june osborn dean of the school of public health at the 
university of michigan said communities need to realistically 
assess whether they have enough hospital beds to accomodate the 
expected surge in aids patients and there should be provision made 
for outpatient care 
osborn also said the nursing shortage poses an ominous threat 
in some areas and she warned that planning is needed to ensure that 
new and experimental aids therapies are available on a equitable 
basis as well as to avoid disastrous competition in hospital 
pharmacy budgets with drugs for other groups of patients 
all of these issues and many more command attention she said 
in her testimony we have an urgent agenda 
