<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday provided a victory 
for women seeking financial support for their illegitimate children 
and the court also expanded its study of drug testing in the 
american workplace 
in a unanimous decision the justices ruled as unconstitutional a 
pennsylvania law that had said the mother of an illegitimate child 
must sue the alleged father for support within six years of the 
childs birth 
the decision hinted that the court might frown on state laws 
preventing mothers from suing on behalf of any minor child in 
effect requiring an 18year deadline for paternity suits 
congress called for such 18year deadlines in the child support 
enforcement amendments of 1984 but the justices passed up the chance 
of ruling whether the federal law is binding on the states 
instead justice sandra day oconnor wrote for the court that 
pennsylvanias former sixyear deadline violated equalprotection 
rights the states law always had let legitimate children sue for 
parental support any time before their 18th birthdays 
diane dodson a lawyer with the womens legal defense fund said 
the ruling represents a second chance for thousands of children 
who were once barred from collecting child support because they 
waited too long to establish paternity 
about 15 million illegitimate children in the united states 
receive no financial support from one parent and ms dodson said as 
many as 400000 might be affected by mondays ruling 
anyone who had been told she waited too long to take her 
childrens father to court to collect child support may be able to 
reopen the matter so long as the children still are under age 18 
she said 
the decision reinstated cherlyn clarks 1983 lawsuit against gene 
jeter for support of her daughter tiffany who was born in 
pittsburgh in 1973 
in a separate action the court said it will decide whether the 
nations railroads may require all employees involved in serious 
accidents to take tests designed to detect alcohol and drug use 
the court agreed to review a feb 11 ruling by the san 
franciscobased 9th us circuit court of appeals that such tests 
conducted by private employers acting for the government are 
unreasonable searches banned by the constitutions fourth amendment 
the railroad drugtesting case stems from regulations issued by 
the federal railroad administration in 1985 to alleviate a 
significant safety problem caused by alcohol and drug use by rail 
employees 
the justices last february said they would decide whether the 
us customs service may conduct drug tests for those seeking 
drugenforcement jobs a federal appeals court condoned such testing 
on monday the justices said they will study the customs service 
and railroad employees cases together a decision is expected 
sometime in 1989 
transportation secretary jim burnley welcomed the courts review 
of the railroad drug tests and predicted the justices would permit 
the tests 
if we can constitutionally test jockeys to protect public 
confidence in the racetrack betting system we surely must be able 
to test railroad operating personnel to protect human lives 
burnley said in a statement 
in other matters the court 
ruled unanimously in a case from colorado that states allowing 
voter initiatives may not prohibit groups from paying those who 
gather the petition signatures necessary to get an issue on the 
ballot 
ruled that two convicted murderers ralph mills in maryland and 
william thomas cartwright in oklahoma were sentenced to death in 
constitutionally unacceptable ways the rulings mean that both men 
are entitled to new sentencing trials 
agreed to return to a confusing area of the law and clarify 
whether or when law enforcement officials may battle drug 
trafficking by stopping and questioning people at airports because 
their characteristics fit that of a drug courier profile 
ruled unanimously in an illinois case that states may offer more 
protection than provided in federal labor law for workers allegedly 
mistreated by their employers 
refused to order states to give refunds to businesses when a 
state tax is invalidated as a violation of interstate commerce the 
justices refused to apply retroactively a 1987 ruling in which they 
struck down a washington state manufacturing tax that favored some 
instate businesses 
</TEXT>
