us defense secretary frank carlucci said monday 
that the west should strengthen controls on its exports to the east 
to keep its technological lead over the soviet bloc 
carlucci said the west should not be lulled by last weeks 
superpower summit in moscow 
until we see some tangible changes we should not change our 
policies he told the japan national press club we are still 
facing a serious military threat 
he said soviet leader mikhail s gorbachevs program of 
perestroika restructuring soviet society and the economy 
emphasizes improving technology carlucci said the soviet union 
traditionally has obtained technology through sources other than its 
own research including stealing it 
carlucci said that the united states has at least a 10year edge 
over the soviet union in computer technology 
the defense secretary said the way to maintain that lead is 
through the coordinating committee for export control which 
regulates technology transfer to communist countries he said 
modifications should be made to tighten restrictions on sensitive 
technology and loosen controls on lowertier technology 
it is vital for our collective security that we seek to 
strengthen cocom carlucci said 
last year a subsidiary of toshiba corp was accused of exporting 
sophisticated technology to the soviet union 
carlucci warned that perestroika could lead to further soviet 
militarization 
if the end result is the west relaxes its defense effort and 
the soviet union modernizes its military and industrial base and 
the soviet union can manufacture enormously more weapons than today 
then we will have made a grave mistake he said 
carlucci arrived in japan last week from moscow to brief leaders 
here on the meeting between president reagan and gorbachev and to 
discuss usjapanese security issues with japans defense and 
governing party officials 
the defense secretary lauded the dialogue between moscow and 
washington that is made easier by the summits 
