<TEXT>
morton thiokol inc which produced the rocket 
booster blamed for the 1986 explosion of the space shuttle 
challenger announced monday it will stay out of competition to 
build an advanced version of the rocket 
the chicagobased company said in a statement it wants to 
concentrate its resources on its immediate task of redesigning the 
booster blamed for the 1986 deaths of seven astronauts shortly after 
takeoff from kennedy space center in florida 
the national aeronautics and space administration plans to use 
thiokols redesigned motor when it resumes shuttle flights nasa 
spokeswoman sarah keegan said monday night from her home in 
washington dc the advanced motor will be used in the mid1990s 
she said 
the companys redesigned solid rocket motor program is almost 
complete with a test firing set for july at cape canaveral fla 
said rocky raab a morton thiokol spokesman in salt lake city utah 
thiokol was the lone manufacturer of shuttle motors and nasa must 
look elsewhere for producers of the new version the advanced solid 
rocket motor 
although bidding has not opened for the advanced motor three 
other parties have expressed an interest in the contract raab said 
he identified them as united technologies the bidding team of 
lockheed and aerojet and another team consisting of hercules 
atlantic research corp and martin marietta 
a presidential commission blamed the deaths of seven astronauts 
including teacher christa mcauliffe seconds after launch on jan 
28 1986 on a plume of hot gas that leaked through a joint in a 
solidfuel booster rocket built by thiokol and ignited the main fuel 
tank thiokol immediately undertook the task of redesigning the 
motor 
reading from a statement keegan said nasa anticipates a 
healthy degree of competition for the asrm advanced motor contract 
when the request for proposals is released and we look forward to 
our continued association with morton thiokol in the curent solid 
rocket motor program 
thiokols decision not to seek the asrm contract follows an 
earlier nasa announcement that the space agency wants to build a 
governmentowned facility to produce the larger rocket motors and 
subcontract with a private manufacturer to operate the plant 
nasa has earmarked 27 million of its current budget for design 
and initial construction of a new booster plant somewhere on the 
gulf coast officials have said they plan to add 65 million from 
next years budget to fund the project and estimate it will take at 
least 10 years to get such a plant funded and operational 
thiokol a manufacturer and marketer of specialty chemicals high 
technology propulsion systems and salt plans to invest 200 million 
in the next several years to modernize its plant in northern utah in 
order to seek other space and defense business raab said 
the plant located 90 miles north of salt lake city is one of 
utahs largest private employers with 2500 workers 
thiokol continues to supply shuttle booster hardware under a 
contract with nasa the company also will build a new 
environmentally controlled building for the redesigned version of 
