<TEXT>
lively and sometimes critical political 
reporting is showing up on the pages of taiwans newspapers as a 
liberalization trend sweeps the island nation 
the zestier coverage began in january when the government lifted 
a 37yearold ban on the establishment of new newspapers and the era 
of rule by chiang kaishek and his family came to an end 
with the market suddenly open to new competition newspapers 
attracted new readers among taiwans 196 million people by breaking 
taboos on stories about the chiang family allegations of 
malfeasance by top officials and highlevel power struggles 
the changes have been substantial although it may take some 
time before we can have the fullfledged freedom the western press 
enjoys said fu cheng a political science professor who was 
jailed for six years after his magazine was banned in 1960 for 
criticizing the chiangs longgoverning nationalist party 
it became clear the old rules no longer applied when newspapers 
exposed a power struggle among nationalist leaders after the death 
of president chiang chingkuo on jan 13 ending a family dynasty 
begun by his father chiang kaishek six decades earlier 
readers were startled by newspaper reports indicating but never 
confirmed that madame chiang kaishek the fathers widow who is in 
her early 90s and now lives in seclusion in suburban taipei was 
behind a lastditch effort to delay the naming of the new president 
lee tenghui as acting party chairman 
this would have been unthinkable just two years ago said hu 
yuanhui a reporter of the liberal independence evening post 
there would have been an order for the shutdown of the 
newspapers 
alice kao deputy editor in chief of the masscirculation united 
daily news said that almost all political taboos were lifted 
overnight and that authorities stopped interfering with news 
coverage so long as newspapers did not espouse communism or question 
the nationalists claim that they should govern mainland china too 
the nationalist government came to power on the mainland early in 
the century but fled to taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war to 
mao tsetungs communists 
the nationalists since have exercised oneparty rule over taiwan 
with the newspaper restrictions a method to allow close government 
control of the media editors frequently received late night 
telephone calls from nationalist officials demanding that 
unfavorable stories be dropped or played down 
ending restrictions on the number of newspapers that could 
publish is part of a recent liberalization program initiated by 
chiang chingkuo before his death the program included the 
scrapping of martial law the formation of opposition parties and 
the release of political prisoners 
among the articles published in taiwan newspapers this year 
reports identifying chiang chingkuos illegitimate twin sons 
one a vice foreign minister and the other the dean of a prominent 
law school 
critical reporting about the military including articles 
suggesting the armed forces may wield too much power 
sensationalized stories that a top taiwanese nuclear scientist 
allegedly worked for the us central intelligence agency and fled 
to the united states with secrets about a nuclear development 
program the nationalist government denies it builds atomic bombs 
expanded coverage of mainland china in part because the 
newspapers have increased in size from the usual 12 pages to 24 a 
maximum they themselves established 
since the media ban was lifted the government has issued 
licenses for about 50 new newspapers meanwhile the existing 30 
newspapers including seven owned by the government and two by the 
nationalist party have upgraded their printing equipment and 
recruited new reporters 
market force dominates now professor fu said the days are 
gone when newspaper reports were twisted under political forces 
opposition politicians however claim that most newspapers still 
do not give prominence to opposition views and activities while 
president lee receives a generally favorable press 
the opposition also notes that taiwans 33 radio stations and 
three television networks remain under government control 
but chang chunhong who heads a research center affiliated with 
the opposition democratic progressive party said that while many 
newspapers remain conservative the important thing is we now have 
a society of many voices 
another sign of the times is that owners of the two largest 
newspaper chains recently submitted their resignations from the 
nationalist partys policymaking central standing committee the 
move is viewed as an effort to improve the newspapers credibility 
</TEXT>
