<TEXT>
the deaths of five students after excessive 
disciplining by teachers over the past three years has raised 
concern about corporal punishment and rigid rules in japanese 
schools 
the death toll is unprecedented said morikatsu imahashi an 
ibaraki university professor specializing on such issues in the 
postwar period up to 1985 there was only one known case where a 
student died of injuries inflicted by a teacher and that was in 
1957 
corporal punishment was banned under japanese law after world war 
ii but following a wave of student violence in the late 1970s 
education officials resurrected rigid rules of prewar times and 
approved physical force in the classroom 
the result imahashi and other critics say is a controlled 
education system but an alarming rise in physical abuse of students 
by teachers 
a growing number of children and adults are starting to 
question the validity of corporal punishment and all those strange 
rules but not enough has been done said yasuhiro yoshimine 
a lawyer and leading member of a juvenile rights committee in the 
japan federation of bar associations 
the first of the five students to die after being punished was 
16yearold toshinau takahashi who in 1985 used a hair dryer in 
violation of school rules his teacher ordered him down on his knees 
and repeatedly hit and kicked him until he fell unconscious with 
mortal head injuries 
a court sentenced the teacher to three years in prison for 
inflicting bodily injury resulting in death in 1987 another 
instructor received the same threeyear sentence for causing the 
classroom death of an 8yearold the other three cases are still 
pending in the courts 
the education ministry said last fall that the number of public 
school teachers fired or suspended for corporal punishment reached a 
record high of 189 in 1986 additionally almost 900 teachers were 
reprimanded or warned for going too far in disciplining their 
students 
with compulsory education to age 15 japan has 217 million 
students in public and private schools from elementary to high 
school 
in a wellpublicized incident in may a teacher in charge of a 
fourday school outing near tokyo beat a student for having a poor 
attitude and then went on to similarly punish 30 others who had 
been ordered to line up in the hallway one by one 
other teachers have attacked students with metal bats or joined 
in groups to punch offending students 
takeshi hayashi 20yearold author of two popular books 
condemning school rules and violent teachers claims schools are 
retreating to the authoritarian pattern of prewar japan by insisting 
that students follow strict dress and behavior codes 
some 90 percent of students in public junior high schools are 
required to wear dark militarystyle suits for boys and sailor 
outfits for girls in the the 1960s only about 10 percent of the 
schools in tokyo had dress codes 
most students today are also expected to cut their hair precisely 
to school specifications wear standard white underwear and adhere 
to an endless list of rules that apply both on and off school 
grounds 
but whats worse is corporal punishment said hayashi who 
has become a teenage hero for writing his books 
physical punishment was an everyday happening in the 
tokyoarea schools he attended he said in an interview 
but he added that his experience paled in comparison to the 
stories recounted in about 3000 letters he received from youths 
around the country 
in my schools teachers never touched the girls then i got 
letters from wayoff places where it seems really wild like 
teachers grabbing girls by the head and chopping off their hair in 
front of the other students just for disobeying hairstyle rules 
following public outcry over recent incidents of alleged teacher 
brutality the education ministry has urged school officials to 
practice moderation in drawing up rules and dealing out punishment 
but sadanobu miwa education professor at chiba university says 
the government should be tackling the education system as a whole 
not just branding teachers as culprits 
japanese schools are pressurecookers where students prepare at 
an early age for difficult extrance examinations for prestigious 
universities 
miwa said those who make it into the teaching profession have 
excelled in the education system but they tend to be underdeveloped 
as human beings 
and it is these people put in front of 40 pupils who turn to 
corporal punishment to control the classroom miwa said 
</TEXT>
