<TEXT>
a technique using microscopic magnetic 
beads may one day be used to discover gum disease long before any 
damage can be done 
the university of connecticut has applied for a patent on the 
technique in which iron beads are coated with a layer of an 
antibody that seeks and binds to cachectin a compound secreted by 
bacteria in early phases of periodontal disease says dr edward f 
rossomando a dentist and biochemist 
the beads in solution are applied between the tooth and gum 
with a syringe only a small drop is required after about five 
minutes the mixture is retrieved with an electromagnetic harvester 
a finetipped probe that picks up the beads the way a magnet picks 
up filings the beads are photographed under a microscope and 
analyzed by computer to measure the cachectin 
eventually it may be used as a screening device in all 
patients rossomando says it also may be used as part of the 
therapy as a way to monitor treatment 
about 30 percent of adults will be diagnosed with gum disease 
after age 35 
