<TEXT>
this year is shaping up as a disaster for north american 
waterfowl and may focus the countrys attention on implementing 
the north american waterfowl management plan to protect and rebuild 
the continents duck populations 
the plan is a 15 billion 15year program by the united states 
and canada and a related agreement with mexico to restore duck 
populations to the levels of the 1950s when estimated fall 
populations totaled about 100 million birds 
with the possibly record drought on the canadian prairies this 
years estimated fall population could fall to near half of that 
this is the most colossal recovery plan ever attempted said 
harvey k nelson who was selected by the us fish and wildlife 
service as the plans first american executive director he said the 
plan was the first opportunity wildlife managers have had to work on 
a continental scale to save ducks 
it is also probably the last opportunity he said 
james h patterson head of the migratory bird branch of the 
canadian wildlife service said if we dont do anything we will 
just have to watch the populations decline and the benefits 
waterfowl provide to our societies will decline as well 
the plan represents a fantastic opportunity for pulling 
together the somewhat desparate interests of the wildlife 
conservation community said charles h chip collins 
executive director of the national fish and wildlife foundation the 
group charged with helping fund the united states 1 billion 
portion of the plan 
in order for the plan to be successful elected officials are 
going to need to be convinced by their constituents that the plan is 
a priority thats why it is important that people understand that 
the plan has a tremendous amount to offer to other species above 
and beyond just waterfowl 
the plan is based on a single principle to have wildlife you 
have to have habitat places for animals to live feed and breed 
it calls for buying some land protecting other land through 
easements and improving the capacity of some land to produce 
waterfowl 
although the drought had accelerated the decline in waterfowl 
the basic reason for the decline is the sometimes seemingly 
inexorable pressures on our landscape the land that has been 
converted over time to other uses including farms and shopping 
centers collins said in an interview 
despite the good efforts of ducks unlimited and state wildlife 
programs and others they simply havent been able to keep pace with 
the pressures weve had on the landscape 
canada and its provinces have taken first steps pledging 
millions of dollars to their shares of the plan in the united 
states the first actual work is to be done this summer 
a dozen states put up 1 million ducks unlimited put up 1 
million and congress doubled the pot canada is adding 4 million 
the money is to be spent in three critical areas the quill lakes 
region of saskatchewan in alberta and in the atlantic flyway where 
the black duck a longtime favorite of eastern waterfowlers is in 
serious trouble collins said 
while the overwhelming bulk of the program involves summer 
breeding habitat in the canadian prairies as well as the upper 
midwest of the united states wintering habitat in the united states 
also is important 
collins said six priority regions have been identified prairie 
habitat the central valley of california the lower mississippi 
valley the gulf coast the atlantic coast from south carolina to 
maine and the eastern great lakes and st lawrence seaway 
joint venture committees of wildlife experts from states 
conservation groups and both countries are working in each of those 
areas identifying areas that must be protected and whether they 
should be purchased or protected by some other means such as an 
easement 
the committees are also looking at other less expensive plans to 
produce and protect wetland habitat 
were looking collins said for a complete set of 
strategies a truly collaborative effort to get these things under 
way 
