american hunters and fishermen pay the majority of the cost of 
wildlife conservation in the united states according to recent 
figures 
this year for example a record 265 million in taxes paid by 
hunters fishermen and boaters will be made available to help 
finance state fish and wildlife restoration programs 
once again hunters and fishermen have made record 
contributions to state fish and wildlife restoration efforts through 
the federal excise taxes they pay on hunting and fishing eqipment 
said secretary of the interior don hodel 
those restoration efforts provide and protect habitat for 
nongame animals as well as the game animals sportsmen pursue for 
example whooping cranes the most endangered of the worlds 15 
species of cranes winter on national wildlife refuges financed by 
waterfowl huters 
this investment by hunters fishermen and supporting industries 
results in many wildlife enhancement activities that will benefit 
all americans said frank dunkle director of the us fish and 
wildlife service 
the two major federal program are the pittmanrobertson program 
which is financed by an 11 percent excise tax on sporting arms and 
ammunition and certain archery equipment and a 10 percent tax on 
handguns 
fisheries and boating projects are financed by the 
dingelljohnson wallopbreaux programs which place a 10 percent 
tax on most fishing tackle and other taxes on other gear used to go 
fishing 
in addition the duck stamp which must be purchased by hunters 
seeking migratory waterfowl brings in millions of dollars each year 
to finance the national wildlife refuge system 
a study by the wildlife conservation fund of america found 
hunters fishermen and trappers paid 11 million in license fees in 
1986 or 534 percent of the revenue collected by state wildlife 
and fisheries agencies federal payments to these agencies the 
return of sportsmens excise taxes contributed another 171 
percent 
other revenue accounted for 134 percent of the wildife 
agencies budgets that included voluntary contributions by 
individual sportsmen as well as the large sums raised by 
