<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday agreed to hear an 
appealstemming from a 19yearold business merger that could 
affect the size of damage awards in some fraud cases 
the court said it will review a ruling in a georgia case that 
limited the ability of purported fraud victims to sue an accounting 
firm 
the case arises out of the 1969 merger of cavalier bag co and 
et barwick industries inc 
the owners of cavalier bag myles guykenneth and robert 
osterneck charged in a 1975 lawsuit that the financial health of 
barwick industries had been overstated 
the osternecks sued barwick officials and ernst amp whinney the 
accounting firm that prepared the allegedly inflated financial 
statements 
after nearly a decade of pretrial maneuvering the case went to 
trial in 1984 and the barwick company and its officials were ordered 
to pay the osternecks more than 26 million in damages plus 
946000 in interest 
but the osternecks lost their case against ernst amp whinney 
they then sought to appeal seeking additional damages from the 
accounting firm 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals ruled that their bid for 
more damages must be treated as a motion to amend the original 
judgment that the osternecks had won 
the appeals court therefore barred the osternecks from pursuing 
their related appeal to bring ernst amp whinney back into the case 
the rules of appellate procedure are designed to prevent 
precisely what has occurred in this case the piecemeal appeal of 
nonfinal substantive judgments rendered by federal judges the 
appeals court said 
the case is osterneck vs ernst amp whinney 871201 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

